    <div class="container">
        <main>
            <!-- EXPOSITORY SECTION: Introduction -->
            <section id="introduction">
                <h2>Welcome to the Ancient Capital</h2>
                <p>
                    Kyoto, formerly the imperial capital of Japan for more than one thousand years, is a city where history breathes in every corner. Unlike the neon-lit skyscrapers of Tokyo, Kyoto offers a landscape of 2,000 temples and shrines, traditional wooden <em>machiya</em> houses, and sublime zen gardens.
                </p>
                <p>
                    It is a city that moves with the seasons—from the cherry blossoms (sakura) of spring to the fiery maples (momiji) of autumn. To visit Kyoto is to step back into a world where tea ceremonies, geisha culture, and meticulous craftsmanship are still a part of daily life.
                </p>
            </section>

            <!-- EXPOSITORY & PERSUASIVE: Attractions -->
            <section id="attractions">
                <h2>Must-See Attractions</h2>
                
                <article>
                    <h3>Fushimi Inari Taisha</h3>
                    <!-- FIGURE & FIGCAPTION Added here -->
                    <figure>
                        <div class="placeholder-image" role="img" aria-label="A visual representation of red Torii gates">
                            [Image: Torii Gates Path]
                        </div>
                        <figcaption>The endless path of vermilion torii gates.</figcaption>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        Famous for its thousands of vermilion torii gates, which straddle a network of trails behind its main buildings, Fushimi Inari is the most important shrine dedicated to Inari, the Shinto god of rice. 
                    </p>
                    <div class="highlight-box">
                        <strong>Why you should go:</strong> The hike to the summit of Mount Inari offers not just spiritual solace but breathtaking views of the city.
                    </div>
                </article>

                <article>
                    <h3>Kinkaku-ji (The Golden Pavilion)</h3>
                    <p>
                        Kinkaku-ji is a Zen temple in northern Kyoto whose top two floors are completely covered in gold leaf. Historically the retirement villa of the shogun Ashikaga Yoshimitsu, it is now one of the most iconic sights in Japan.
                    </p>
                    <div class="highlight-box">
                        <strong>Why you should go:</strong> Watching the golden reflection of the temple shimmering across the Kyoko-chi (Mirror Pond) is a moment of pure serenity that defines the Japanese aesthetic.
                    </div>
                </article>
            </section>

            <!-- PERSUASIVE SECTION: Why Visit -->
            <section id="why-visit">
                <h2>Why Kyoto Will Change You</h2>
                <p>
                    Kyoto isn't just a sightseeing destination; it's an experience that alters your perspective on pace and beauty.
                </p>
                
                <article>
                    <h3>1. Mindfulness & Zen</h3>
                    <p>The city's Zen gardens, such as Ryoan-ji, provide a perfect backdrop for meditation. In a world of constant noise, Kyoto teaches the value of silence.</p>
                </article>

                <article>
                    <h3>2. Culinary Excellence</h3>
                    <p>Experience <em>Kaiseki</em>, the traditional multi-course Japanese dinner that is as much art as it is food. Every dish honors the season and the ingredient.</p>
                </article>
            </section>

            <!-- QUOTES SECTION -->
            <section id="quotes">
                <h2>Traveler's Wisdom</h2>
                
                <blockquote cite="https://www.goodreads.com/quotes/tag/kyoto">
                    "Kyoto is a city that doesn't just show you its beauty; it asks you to slow down and notice it. It is the whisper of Japan compared to Tokyo's shout."
                    <cite>— Modern Travel Blog</cite>
                </blockquote>

                <blockquote cite="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matsuo_Bash%C5%8D">
                    "Even in Kyoto,<br>
                    hearing the cuckoo's cry,<br>
                    I long for Kyoto."
                    <cite>— Matsuo Basho (Haiku Master)</cite>
                </blockquote>
            </section>
        </main>

        <!-- ASIDE SECTION (Added for extra credit/completeness) -->
        <aside>
            <h3>Quick Facts</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <strong>Best Time to Visit</strong>
                    Spring (Cherry Blossoms) or Autumn (Fall Foliage).
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Currency</strong>
                    Japanese Yen (¥)
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Transport</strong>
                    Kyoto is best explored by bus or bicycle. The subway lines are limited but useful.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Did you know?</strong>
                    Kyoto was the capital of Japan from 794 to 1868.
                </li>
            </ul>
        </aside>
